MALE NARRATOR
Why do companies go global? The benefits are substantial.

Benefit 1: Economies of Scale
When you serve large market segments across multiple countries, you can produce at massive scale. This reduces per-unit costs and creates competitive advantages.
Apple designs one iPhone but sells it worldwide. The R&D cost is spread across hundreds of millions of units. That's economies of scale.

Benefit 2: Knowledge Transfer
Operating globally allows you to transfer experience and know-how across countries. Best practices developed in one market can be applied to others.
McDonald's perfected operational efficiency in the US and transferred it globally. Toyota's lean manufacturing, developed in Japan, revolutionized auto manufacturing worldwide.

Benefit 3: Access to Tough Customers
Marketing globally exposes you to the world's most demanding customers. If you can satisfy them, you become better everywhere.
Indian IT companies learned by serving demanding US and European clients. This made them world-class.

Benefit 4: Financial Diversification
When you operate in multiple markets, you're not dependent on one economy. If one market slows down, others may thrive.
This diversity provides financial stability and reduces risk.

Benefit 5: Exploiting Changing Financial Circumstances
Global companies can take advantage of currency fluctuations, tax regimes, and economic conditions across markets.
They can manufacture in low-cost countries, sell in high-income markets, and optimize their financial structure globally.

These benefits explain why companies aspire to go global. But the path is not easy. In Video 2, we'll explore the eight critical challenges of global marketing, using real-world examples from Nike and Domino's.

